Related C++ code:
  - check_mouse_round_rect corresponds to inline hit-test code duplicated across multiple C++ widget CheckMouse methods:
    - src/emCore/emButton.cpp lines 278-281: `dx=emMax(emMax(x-mx,mx-x-w)+r,0.0); dy=emMax(emMax(y-my,my-y-h)+r,0.0); *pHit = dx*dx+dy*dy <= r*r;`
    - src/emCore/emScalarField.cpp:307 — CheckMouse method with similar formula
    - src/emCore/emTextField.cpp:880 — CheckMouse method with similar formula
  - In C++, each widget class has its own copy of this formula inline in its CheckMouse method. Rust extracts the common formula into a shared utility function.
  - trace_input_enabled has no C++ equivalent — it is a Rust-only debugging aid.
  - Structural differences: C++ duplicates the round-rect hit-test formula in each widget's CheckMouse. Rust deduplicates into widget_utils.rs. The formula is identical: `dx = max(max(rect.x - mx, mx - rect.x - rect.w) + r, 0); dy = ...; hit = dx*dx + dy*dy <= r*r`.

OPEN QUESTIONS:
  - The file was created during "Phase 3" restructuring. It may have previously been inline code in individual widget files, or it may have been created fresh as a deduplication during the rename.
  - trace_input_enabled uses OnceLock (from std::sync). The CLAUDE.md rules say "no Arc/Mutex — single-threaded UI tree". OnceLock is not Arc/Mutex but is a sync primitive; whether this is considered an exception is unclear.
